reviewText: I knew little about "She's the Man" before I bought the dvd. I bought this movie because of the ads and reviews I've seen and because I happen to like Channing Tatum (who was fab in "Step Up") and Amanda Bynes.  I also happen to enjoy "Twelfth Night" and the fact that this movie 'lifts' from its story did not escape my notice. Now that I've seen it a few times I certainly would consider this a keeper. It's a movie that my whole family can enjoy.The plot has already been covered by most other reviewers. Amanda Bynes succeeds in this because of her pure comedic talents. She does well as tomboy-ish, soccer-loving, rough-around-the-edges Viola and also as the 'fake' goofy and awkward twin brother Sebastian.  Her crazy antics as a girl-pretending-to-be-a-boy are often hilarious and this movie has surprisingly good writing and engaging characters.  I especially like Tatum (very easy on the eye) as soccer star Duke Orsino, Duke's hapless best friends, Viola's frustrated socialite mother, Vinnie Jones as the scene-stealing soccer coach, and David Cross as the eccentric principal.Most people would dismiss this as a movie geared towards teenagers but, like "Clueless" and "10 Things I Hate About You" before it (which are also loosely based on famous classic literary works), it is actually a clever film and one that a wide range of age groups would enjoy.  It's wacky, laugh-out-loud funny and, most importantly, it's one of those films that the whole family can enjoy.
summary: Loads of fun. This movie is hilarious!

reviewText: Funny for sure, `She's the Man' isn't the perfect teen comedy (can't hold a candle to the likes of `Mean Girls' or '10 Things I Have About You') but it has enough going for it to constitute a viewing or two.  With the `ever so spunky' Amanda Bynes and the new age heartthrob Channing Tatum (my wife drools and begs me to do more sit-ups), `She's the Man' has enough eye-candy for both genders, not to mention humor both can enjoy and a storyline (straight from Shakespeare) that is engaging, entertaining and memorable.Viola likes to play soccer, but when her school drops the girl's soccer team she finds herself out of luck.  When her brother, Sebastian, decides to ditch school for a chance to play with his band in London, Viola decides to take his place (it's a new school, and she's his twin, so no one should notice; right?) in order to play on their soccer team and defeat her old school's boy's soccer team (who refused to let her join).  Then she falls in love with Duke, her (his) roommate.  Duke is in love with Olivia, and he asks Sebastian (Viola) to hook him up, but Olivia ends up falling for Sebastian instead.It's a mess all around, but it's a funny mess.The acting is fine for a film of this nature.  Bynes is a delightful over-actor (I've mentioned my adoration of her recently) but here she grates my nerves a tad when she's in Sebastian mode.  Her Viola is stunning, charming and endearing.  Her Sebastian is rather forced and unbelievable; but I think that's what they were going for.The rest of the cast is a bunch of hot young things that are just as serviceable as the next flock of hot young things, with no real standout aside from Channing, who is really a notch above the rest to be honest.  He's actually got some talent to back up that six-pack.  I also really liked Vinnie Jones here; as the soccer coach Dinklage.For those of you who enjoy a good teen comedy then this one is a surefire hit.  It has all the elements to make an enjoyable, if rather brainless, cinematic experience.  It's nice to turn off every once in a while, and this provides the desired escape.  If you're a fan of Bynes or any of her movies then this will not disappoint.  It has it's quirks (what movie of this genre doesn't) but it makes up for them in other areas and delivers a pretty solid and enjoyable teen movie.

reviewText: "She's the Man" is a perfect weekend movie.  It's easy to understand, the actors are all pretty good-looking, and it gives some great laughs.Based loosely on Shakespeare's "Twelfth Night", this film tells the story of high-schooler Viola Hastings (Bynes), a star soccer player.  When the girls team at her school gets cut due to lack of sign-ups, she wants to try out for the boys team.  When the coach laughs in her face and tells her that girls can never beat boys, Viola impersonates her twin brother to join the team of the rival school.  Predictably, Viola finds that twisted love triangles are a lot more complicated when she's a girl pretending to be a boy.This plot is much easier to digest on screen.  As Viola, Amanda Bynes is at her comedic best!  Her facial expressions and confidence will keep you laughing throughout nearly the entire movie.Some lines are unnecessarily dramatic, however, and the actors' best efforts cannot keep these parts of the script from being corny.  At points "She's the Man" also requires viewers to suspend reality.  The high schools seem more like colleges (dorms, full-size stadiums) and, though they can pass as twins, Viola and Sebastian (the brother she impersonates) certainly don't look enough alike to carry off such an audacious plan.To sum things up, if you are able to forgive the corny scenes and abandon reality for 105 minutes, you will get a good laugh and some endorphins out of this film.4-stars...give it a try!

reviewText: There are two minor, yet central problems with "She's the Man."  The most obvious is the fact that this story has been done in various ways and countless times over the years:  From the most obvious comparison "Just One of the Guys (1985)," to more recent junk like "White Chicks," and "The Hot Chick" (to run down the long list of examples would take all night and this entire page).  The mistaken identity and trading places comedies are as tried and true a lazy film fallback genre as the teen slasher flick or underdog team sports movies ("She's the Man" even throws in this clieche for good measure).  And just like "Ten Things I hate About You," "O," and "She's All That" before it, "She's The Man" lifts from the Bard; this time "updating" his "Twelfth Night."But the great, surprising thing about "She's the Man" is that it's better than most of its type, and far funnier.  Most of the credit for this must go to the surprisingly fabulous Amanda Bynes who has a real gift for comic timing, is rather fearless, and is also very cute.  Almost all by herself, she not only saves a rather mediocer movie from itself, but she elevates it and makes it something more.  But that also brings us to the second problem with this film; something I like to call the Jessica Alba/"Fantastic Four" mistake.  When you have stars as appealing and beautiful as these, you do not cast them as the invisible woman or a guy for a majority of the film.  There is a scene about 45 minutes into this movie where Bynes has been in disguise for over a half an hour or so; she rips her wig off and it is just a seething reminder that you do not like to see her as a man.  But absence makes the heart grow fonder, so it goes without saying that every time she pulls off her stupid drag wig throughout the movie it works to the same effect.The movie is also witty and well written, at least in the early going.  It takes no major skill to write jokes about how men differ from women; but again, it is the line readings and the deadpanning from Bynes that makes all of this seem so much smarter and funnier than any of this has any right to be.  There is a silly, smartassness to the script that pops up every once in awhile ("This has been fun, but I gotta go, um, shave!"  "What does your heart tell you?  Er, um, I mean, which one would you rather see NECKED?!"  There's a ton of them, all of them that much better due to Bynes' game delivery) and some of the supporting performances, esspecialy from David Cross as the school dean and the soccer coach, add a welsome absurdity to the script.I thought it was also winkingly funny that they cast a dead ringer for Lindsey Lohan as the "mean girl" in this film.  The entire scene in a pizza parlor about a half hour in to the movie warrants repeat viewing, as does a workout scene in the gym, and Bynes' eating habbits at a formal rehearsal. But the dumb romantic triangle that creeps in halfway through the story and the predictable way it all plays out almost blows a lot of the good will the writers have earned up to that point (indeed, the guys, and most everyone over 17, will be rolling their eyes though much of this).  It seems that with a little more work this could have been a much smarter and more original comedy that would actually have the chance of standing out and earning a lot of praise.  As it is it takes the easy way out, but Bynes still manages to rise above it and the film itself still manages to earn enough laughs (again, mostly thanks to Bynes) to place it ahead of its similar counterparts.Also consider that this film's key demo is likely not to care about any of the gripes I had.  I'm sure this is just what teen girls want.  As such, they could do a lot worse."She's the Man" is technically noting special, even though Bynes is, but I can't deny it made me laugh more than I thought it would.  It was truely a pleasent surprise.So... 3 1/2 out of Amazon's 5 stars, but more acurately, 3 stars out of the standard 4.
summary: 5 Stars for Bynes, but the movie has been done.

reviewText: 'She's the Man' released in '06 is an enjoyable though predictable tale of a talented teenage soccer player named Viola (Amanda Bynes) who also happens to be an attractive girl attending a high school that just disbanded its girl's soccer team. When the soccer coach refuses to give her a tryout with the boy's squad she devises a plan to take her twin brothers place at another local school and pretend to be a male. Of course the usual love interests and emotional complications develop along the way and jeporadize her role-playing act and percarious position on the boy's team.Nothing new here, it's a movie you've seen many times in one form or another. However the cast is attractive and the acting is better than you might expect. Channing Tatum does a great job as Duke, Viola's love interest as does Laura Ramsey as Olivia. However the real strength of the film is the lovely and talented Amanda Bynes. If you're an Amanda fan like I am you'll love it. If not you'll probably like it anyway.
summary: "That's Me!" ~ Amana Bynes Scores On And Off The Soccer Field

reviewText: I wasn't surprised at how much I enjoyed watching SHE'S THE MAN. Amanda Bynes is a cut above all the other teen actress scoring movie role after movie role these days, especially when it comes to doing comedy. She scored HER OWN Nickelodean variety show, THE AMANDA SHOW, at the ripe old age of 13.She's a natural. Uninhibited. Loose. Funny. The 4 years she spent on her skit show have paid off. She's a joy to watch. Her facial reactions and her goofiness are engaging. Then you throw in the fact that she, for the majority of the movie, is playing a young girl named Viola who is pretending to be her twin brother Sebastian so she can play soccer on a men's team because her girls team got cut, and you have the makings of a good film.Yet, there's something more going on in SHE'S THE MAN. There were numerous times in the movie that I caught myself busting out laughing... and not always at Amanda. The writer's of the film did a good job of engaging the audience and not letting them go.There are rich characters throughout. Channing Tatum plays Duke, a soccer stud and Viola/Sebastian's roommate, who is a complete basketcase when he gets around Olivia, played by a very attractive Laura Ramsey, who is infatuated with Sebastian/Viola, who is falling for Duke and trying to fight off Sebastian's real girlfriend, who keeps trying to find out why he or Viola broke up with her.It's a movie that never rests and is always moving and twisting and becoming more and more entertwined. All the while, being very very funny.The only thing I had a problem with was from time to time, some pretty film reality things happened... in other words... yeah right occurences. Not to mention, some pretty unbelievable soccer occurences. I guess anytime a movie tries to do a sporting event, it very rarely looks believable, and this is no exception. Although, the writers had the GREAT common sense to throw in some solid comic moments that make you forget you're watching some pretty unrealistic stuff and even though you are, you're still smiling.I mean, come on... you can't beat the line, "Is it just me, or is there more nudity in this soccer game than most?"

reviewText: `She's the Man' is actually quite good, and while not the perfect teen comedy (still can't beat the likes of `Mean Girls') it succeeds because the cast is fresh and likable.  I'm a fan of Amanda Bynes despite the fact that she's a chronic over actor, and here she is likable despite that flaw (she's not so bad when playing Viola, but when imitating her brother Sebastian she can be borderline annoying).The story revolves around Viola (Bynes) who is obsessed with playing women's soccer.  When the girl's soccer team is cut from her school and the boys team refuses to allow the girls to join Viola decides to try another route.  With her twin brother Sebastian (Kirk) ditching his first few weeks at his new school, Illyria, for an opportunity to play with his band in London, Viola disguises herself as her brother in order to get on the boys soccer team and win the match against her old school, Cornwall, proving that girls can play as well as boys.  What she never counted on was falling in love with her roommate Duke (Channing Tatum) who is in love with Olivia (Laura Ramsey).  When Duke asks Sebastian to hook him up with Olivia neither of them expected Olivia to fall for Sebastian.Truly enjoyable and full of laughs, `She's the Man' is a worthwhile watch through and will provide the viewer with enough eye candy and enough likeability to make it memorable.  Each of the actors, from Bynes and Tatum to supporting players like David Cross and `Lock Stock and Two Smoking Barrels' star Vinnie Jones (who plays the soccer coach for Illyria brilliantly), do a great job in delivering an enjoyable film the whole family can enjoy.

reviewText: Loosely based on Shakespeare's "Twelfth Night", this movie is a great complement to any unit covering the play. I used to show my students the Helena Bonham-Carter movie "Twelfth Night" (Also very good, very funny) after reading the play with them. As Shakespeare's humor was often lost just reading the play, watching it being acted out definitely helped students to "get it." Amazing, but the play is still funny 500 years later. One year decided to opt for this version instead. Though not as faithful to the Bard, kids REALLY enjoyed the film, laughing at all the ensuing chaos when the twins (Viola and Sebastian) are mistaken for each other. Great acting. Very funny film in its own right (ie, you don't have to study "Twelfth Night" to show/appreciate it).If one is teaching "Twelfth Night", can't go wrong with either film, but I'm a bit more partial to this one. It's just funnier.

reviewText: Amanda Bynes shows a real knack for comedy in this modern version of "Twelfth Night."  When Viola learns that the girls soccer team was cut at her school, she disguises herself as her twin brother, Sebastian (who's in London for two weeks), and tries out for the boy's team at his school to prove that girls are just as good athletes as boys.  In the process, she falls for her roommate who thinks she's a boy, and who she's promised to help out with winning the heart of his crush, Olivia (who ends up falling for Viola disguised as Sebastian). reviewText: When the girls' soccer team at her high school is cut due to a lack of participation, Viola Hastings decides to take advantage of her twin brother's impromptu trip to London and join the soccer team at his new school.  To complete her transformation, she wears a short wig, binds her breasts, and practices talking and actling like a guy.  What she doesn't expect is how difficult it will be to be a first-string player at her new school, or that she might fall for her brother's roommate, Duke Orsino.In case you didn't know, this movie is based on Shakespeare's Twelfth Night.  What you also might not know is that this movie borrows heavily from the 80's flick Just One of The Guys.  In fact, the first thirty minutes of the movie is basically Just One of The Guys with soccer instead of journalism.  I'm all for remakes and creative reinvention, but I also think the makers of this film need to give credit where credit is due.  While the love story is the same pattern as Twelfth Night and the characters have the same names, for all intents and purposes it's basically just a JOTG remake.Other than that blatant omission, I liked this movie well enough.  Channing Tatum is my new teen crush and since he spent more than half the movie with his shirt off, that was good enough for me.  If you like JOTG or if you like this movie, I'd say you'd probably like the other as well.  If you haven't seen either, it's just another teen movie.  It has its funny moments, but it's not necessarily a must-buy.
summary: "Girls can't beat boys, it's as simple as that"

reviewText: When it comes to thinking outside of the box on the plays of William Shakespeare, I am inclined to point back to 1936 when the Federal Theater Projects assigned Orson Welles to direct a project in Harlem.  Welles mounted a production of "Macbeth" set in Haiti at the court of King Henri Christophe that was wildly successful.  After World War II on the other side of the world Akira Kurosawa did his own versions of "Macbeth" and "King Lear," as "Throne of Blood" and "Ran" respectively.  Then we come to a pivotal moment in the history of Shakespeare when the musical "West Side Story," written by Arthur Laurents (book), Leonard Bernstein (music), and Stephen Sondheim (lyrics), which took "The Tragedy of Romeo & Juliet" and turned the family strife between the Montaques and the Capulets into a turf ware on the lower east side of New York City between the Jets and the Sharks.  True, "Kiss Me Katetook "The Taming of the Shrew" and made it part of a musical in a musical, but "West Side Story" was important because it was the movie that said Shakespeare is for kids.That is why in recent years we have seen both Shakespearean tragedies like "Othello" and comedies such as "The Taming of the Shrew," set in the world of teenage angst in the films "O)" and "10 Things I Hate About You."  In addition to both of those films having Julia Stiles as the female lead, they were both relatively serious films, at least in terms of pretending they took place in the realm world.  But "She's the Man" is a version of Shakespeare's "Twelfth Night" that is totally willing to play up the comedy, going more for slapstick (although the catfight in the ladies room between the three principle young women in the cast is rather violent slapstick).  So this really gets beyond the tongue in cheek stage.If you know "Twelfth Night" then you will be able to figure this one out.  If not, the film's tagline explains it all: "Duke (Channing Tatum) wants Olivia (Laura Ramsey) who likes Sebastian (James Kirk) who is really Viola (Amanda Bynes) whose brother is dating Monique (Alex Breckenridge) so she hates Olivia (Laura Ramsey) who's with Duke (Channing Tatum) to make Sebastian (James Kirk) jealous who is really Viola (Amanda Bynes) who's crushing on Duke (Channing Tatum) who thinks she's a guy..."  So basically it is a love story complicated by mistaken identity, which for most of the film involves three people being four until the fourth shows up and helps everything work out.  The screenplay by Ewan Leslie, Karen McCullah Lutz and Kristen Smith is able to streamline things a bit by having Viola pretend to be her brother Sebastian, instead of pretending to be a boy named Cesario (which is now the name of a pizza joint), so that when Sebastian shows up people think he is Sebastian, which he is, only not the Sebastian they know that is really Viola, and not Cesario, whom he is not.The other key change is that Shakespeare did not write about football (what we Yanks call soccer), which is what Viola plays.  But Cornwall High cuts its girls soccer team and she is not allowed to try out for the boys team, she decides the only thing to do is to take advantage of her brother's quick trip to London to play music to go to his school, Illyria, and make their boys soccer team so when they play Cornwall, she can beat them and show them (which, in more than one way, she does).  This is a world where the adults stay mostly out of the way, and I was going to say that with Viola and Sebastian's mom (Julie Hagerty) and Principal Gold (David Cross) that this was sort of like the Charlie Brown world where the grownups just make noise, except Vinnie Jones shows up to play Coach Dinklage, and I dare any of you to tell him what he says is meaningless.This is a fun movie.  Bynes is not trying too hard, which is what is just what is needed for the role at the center of "She's the Man."  If she tried any less, then it would just be total silliness from start to finish.  But if she tried any harder then we would have to deal with the obvious fact that she does not look like a boy and that her Sebastian is a lot shorter than the real Sebastian.  On stage when you see "Twelfth Night" performed this is always the case, but we go along with that, so certainly a movie that is based on it deserves the same consideration.  Fortunately Bynes is still associated much more with Nickelodeon than the tabloids so her aura of innocence and inherent likeability allow us to enjoy the nonsense and just go ahead for the ride.  It will be some time before we get around to the likes of "Titus Andronicus" set in a high school, but you know the day is coming, so lighthearted fare such as ""She's the Man" is a fun movie to watch in the meantime.
summary: "Twelfth Night" set in a high school, but with more nudity in the soccer game than usual

reviewText: Director Andy Fickman who led "Reefer Madness" and has "The Game Plan" coming out with Kyra Sedgwick & The Rock does a good job of keeping the pace brisk and the comedy bubbly in this sweet comedy.  Amanda Bynes displays great comic skills as the lead in this film.  The situations that arise from a girl trying to pass as a guy are as hilarious as they are at times embarrassing, reference the locker scene where the towel comes off.  James N. Kirk from both X-Men films does a good job as her brother Sebastian whose need to head for London with his band and miss the first two weeks of school sets up the twisted plot.  Channing Tatum from "Step Up," "Coach Carter" & "Supercross" does an excellent job as Duke, the jock roommate who has a romantic side as he looks for the right girl.  Laura Ramsey who is in "The Covenant" stars as the popular Olivia that Duke dates.  Julie Hagerty gives a great cameo performance as the addled mother Daphne.  David Cross as the bald Principal Gold who keeps trying to give words of wisdom to his students that are as inappropriate as they are misguided gives another fine performance.  Cross is one of those actors that frequents screens in films like "School for Scoundrels," "Eternal Sunshine of the Spotless Mind," "Men In Black" & "The Truth About Cats & Dogs."  The improbable situations are hilarious.  The climactic soccer match causes Sebastian to drop his drawers and Amanda Bynes to bare her bosom, all out of sight of the PG-13 cameras.  This is an enjoyable little romp that will not weigh on your mind but gives good chuckle!  Enjoy!

reviewText: First came "10 Things I Hate About You", a contemptable and miserable teen modernization of Shakespeare's "The Taming of the Shrew" and now director Andy Fickman brings us "She's the Man" yet another teen-targeted modernization, this time of Shakespeare's "Twelfth Night, or What You Will".  Like "10 Things", "She's the Man" is loosely based on the Shakespeare play, but absolutely does not offer a replacement for the Shakespeare text.  My theory is that filmmakers have the public pretense of getting high-school-age kids to be more, shall we say, involved with Shakespeare, only to make a tragedy (or perhaps travesty) out of brilliant Shakespeare comedies.  Amanda Bynes, popularized by her Nickelodeon show and her previous roles in "Big Fat Liar" and the tween "What a Girl Wants", plays Viola, a young girl forced to impersonate her twin brother Sebastian (James Kirk) after he conveniently jets off to England for two weeks (whereas, in the play, Viola believes her brother to be dead, and her name becomes Cesario).  Whilst impersonating her brother, Viola must make everyone at the Illyria Prep. school (no doubt inspired by the setting of "Twelfth Night") believe she is Sebastian.  Is this possible?  Absolutely not.  Would she pass for a boy?  Doubt it.  The film seems to stick to the basic plot line of "Twelfth Night" and Viola/Sebastian finds herself crushing on Duke (no doubt inspired by Duke Orsino in the play), played by a miscast Channing Tatum.  While I'm on the subject, I must reiterate a fact that I discovered while reading Roger Ebert's review (and an overgenerous review at that) of this film.  Channing Tatum, in real life, is 26 years old.  I half expected the filmmakers to be ex-90210 casting directors.  Is it really that much of a necessity to cast a 26-year-old to play a high school student?  I won't let you think about that too long before telling you that it isn't necessary.  It usually helps even more to cast a good actor for this film, as well as other films, and Tatum is not (see the dopey "Step Up").  Viola finds herself in a bind, wanting Duke, but, alas, she must go on impersonating her brother.  Duke finds himself after the moody Olivia (much different from the Shakespeare), played by Laura Ramsey, who in turn, finds herself after Viola, who she thinks is Sebastian.  Hilarity (or something posing as hilarity) ensues in a final scene, semi-close to the final act in "Twelfth Night" and then I realized that I had wasted my time.  This film does not serve as a parallel to Shakespeare, and absolutely does not work in any of the ways the play does.  There are brilliant characters in the Shakespeare who are dulled down in this version, probably to keep up with the PG-13 rating, like Sir Andrew, Sir Toby, Maria, and the ever-entertaining Feste.  If you are looking for a better version of "Twelfth Night" on film, check out Trevor Nunn's 1996 film of the same name, starring Helena Bonham Carter, Ben Kingsley (as Feste), Imelda Staunton, and the hilarious Nigel Hawthorne as Malvolio.

reviewText: What to do, if you are a girl that wants to play soccer and the girl's team of your high school has been cut? If you are Viola  (Amanda Bynes), you convince your friends to help you and disguise yourself as your brother Sebastian (James Kirk), in order to try out for the boys' team of other school. After all, "If you can't join them, beat them".That's is the starting point of a delightful comedy of errors, that is more than a little silly, but pretty funny all the same. What will Viola do when she falls for Duke (Channing Tatum), one of her teammates? And how will she escape from Olivia (Laura Ramsey), the girl Duke loves but that happens to have a crush on "Sebastian"?I'm quite sure you will not be more intelligent after watching "She is the man", but I am also confident that you will have had lots of fun, specially if you are under 20, or someone older who still likes a silly but engaging movie from time to time. Recommended!Belen Alcat

reviewText: If you want to see a contemporary teen remake of a Shakespeare play, don't bother with this mess that is loosely (very loosely) based on "Twelfth Night".  Amanda Bynes is cute, and maybe she's a good actress, but to tell you the truth with the script and direction that she was given to work with, we may never know.The names are the same as the characters from Shakespeare, and the basic premise of a woman pretending to be a man is there.  But the Elizabethan era Viola, Sebastian, Olivia and Duke Orsino have a much, much more coherent story line.  Here, Viola is moved to assume a masculine identity so she can play soccer.  But oops, while she plays well against the girls or in her bikini against the boys, she seems to lose all ability once she tries out for the boys varsity.If watching a goofball comedy, with attractive teenagers is what you're looking for, be my guest, just don't expect even the semblance of believability.  If you would rather see a decent attempt (not a great attempt mind you, but a decent one), check out "Ten Things I Hate About You" for an American teen update on "Taming of the Shrew."  At least that one has Julia Stiles and Heath Ledger!
summary: Three Stars for Ambition... One Star for Execution, Let's just split the difference.

reviewText: Soccer-playing Viola (Bynes) is really upset when the girls' soccer team is cut.  The boys' team does not want any girls on it, so Viola decides to impersonate her brother Sebastian (Kirk), who conveniently is starting a new school where he is unknown.  He is also skipping out of the first weeks of school in order to pursue a musical career in Europe.  Being Sebastian, she can play soccer, and maybe even get some revenge on her own school's team.Everything is going well for Viola until she falls in love with her roommate (Tatum).  Of course, he is interested in Olivia (Ramsey), and Olivia has got her eye on Viola.  The only thing that could make things more complicated for Viola is if her brother were to come home early.  And he does."She's the Man" is loosly based on William Shakespeare's "Twelfth Night", and works pretty well.  The majority of this film's success is due to Amanda Bynes as Viola.  While never really looking like a guy, she has the enthusiasm and screen presence to make this an enjoyable film.  Although aimed primarily at the teen audience, others will find enjoyment in it too.

reviewText: Viola (Amanda Bynes) wants to join the boys soccer team, but this wish causes her to break up with her boyfriend (Robert Hoffman). Eventually, she finds herself disguised as her brother Sebastian (James N. Kirk), and attending Illyria Prep school. When Viola is assigned a shared dorm room with campus cool guy Duke (Channing Tatum), her fa�ade slowly begins to crumple as she begins harboring a deep-rooted crush on her unsuspecting new roommate. The situation begins to take a turn for the worse, however, when Duke reveals his affection towards campus knockout Olivia (Laura Ransey), who in turn seems increasingly drawn towards the sensitive impostor known as Sebastian. The problem is, the real Sebastian has decided to cut his London trip short, and upon arriving on campus two days earlier than expected, Viola's elaborately execute ruse hits an unexpected hitch that sends the entire situation spiraling into chaos.Amongst the hype of Lindsay Lohan and Hillary Duff, there's another young actress ready to break out big time: Amanda Bynes. Fresh from doing sketch shows like "All That", Bynes has appeared in comedies like "Big Fat Liar" and, in her first leading role, "What A Girl Wants". Sadly, critics haven't been too appeased, despite her charms and decent comic timing. Enter "She's The Man", based on William Shakespeare's play "Twelvth Night".Directed by Andy Fickman ("Reefer Madness: The Musical"), "She's The Man" kicks off as a growing-up party for Amanda Bynes, where we get to see her in a bikini top and jeans. And, honestly, she looks really good. However, Fickman kind of gets lost in teen movie clich�s 101. While it's cool to hear Bynes say "bi-atch" and "you suck", it's the world she's populated in: a geeky villain (played by James Snyder), a typically sexy love interest, and a soundtrack comprised of punk rock and girly pop. Plus, it doesn't go above and beyond gender-bending clich�s. There is comic potential here, but with an overdose of subplots, and the PG-13 rating, it fails.But, as I already stated, at least Bynes is reliable to turn in a good performance. Despite the fact that she is not capable of being bought as a boy (maybe she should've watched "Transamerica"), at least she can mug her way and deliver some funny lines to stay above Fickman's lame direction.There are a couple mixed bag performances. Julia Hagerty reprises her role from "Just Friends" as an over-the-top mother, Channing Tatum is surprisingly funny even for a love interest of a girl, and David Cross is sadly underused and wasted.Much like with Amy Smart, Bynes is a surprisingly talented - and underrated - comic actress (and it doesn't hurt that she did sketch comedy at a young age) whose talents deserve to be in a larger-scaled project. And she looks really good at 19 going on 20. "She's the Man" is not a bad piece of work, but one wonders if they hired a better director who can avoid teen movie clich�s and make something like "Mean Girls". Maybe Amanda should get in bed with Tina Fey.
summary: "Sexual tension, male female dynamics... all part of the high school experience..."

reviewText: I really enjoyed this film. It stars a teen girl (Viola) who longs to be a soccer player. When her team gets cut she joins the team of her twin brother's school disguised as him. The ensuing misunderstandings and troubles this causes complicate both their lives.I really loved the film. I admit I was a little leery when I read this was derived from Shakespeare's 12th night. I know it is plebian but I loathe Shakespeare and don't care for remakes.  However this film is thoroughly modern and thoroughly funny.I particularly enjoyed Viola's male roommate, her hairdresser buddy and the interaction between Vi and her new jock friends. 5 stars.

reviewText: Let me start by saying that I am neither a fan of chick flicks, nor had I ever heard of Amanda Bynes prior to viewing "She's the Man" only a couple of days ago. However, based on this movie alone, I hope Ms Bynes has a long comedic career. Her ability to entertain a viewer would be uncanny and sophisticated even for a more mature performer.The story is simple: a girl has a girl power problem and decides the only way out is to spend two weeks mascarading as her own twin brother. Throw in a cute boy, soccer, and a few high stung adults... voila! hilarity and light hearted drama ensue. Hard to believe I did not catch this movie when it was out three years ago... Shame on me!

reviewText: After being told she can't play on the guys soccer team, Viola (Amanda Bynes) does the unthinkable.  While her twin brother Sebastian goes to London to pursue a music career, Viola pretends to be him and dresses up like him, just to play on the boys' soccer team at his school.  When she goes to Sebastian's school as Sebastian, she falls for one of the teammates named Duke.  Things get complicated when a girl named Olivia falls for Sebastian (who is really Viola).  Viola isn't interested (cuz she's a girl lol), so Olivia hits on Duke to make Sebastian (Viola) jealous."She's The Man" is a great movie!  It's funny and it has a great moral; girls can do anything guys can do, if not better.

reviewText: Amanda Bynes is one of the most gifted natural comics in Hollywood, and this hybridized adaptation of Twelfth Night is another excellent vehicle for her talents.Shakespeare himself understood the fun that can arise when gender identification becomes blurred, as in his plays Twelfth Night and As You Like It, above all.Amanda carries off both roles brilliantly, in a performance that cashes in on her stunning grasp of physical comedy.The cross-dressing and accidental same-sex crushes reminded me of the tag line from the superb Helena Bonham Carter/Ben Kingsley version of Twelfth Night... Never send a boy to do a  man's job, especially if he's a she...Excellent.

reviewText: The first step to take to enjoy this movie is to realize that it is meant to be a silly light hearted comedy.  If you can't allow yourself to let go of the details you can't watch this movie.Amanda Byrnes plays Viola a soccer loving teen.  Viola's soccer team is cut and she is not allowed to try out for the boys team.  When Viola learns that her brother Sebastian is ditching school for a few weeks Viola decides to become him so she can prove she can play on the boys team.Of course all sorts of wackiness ensues as Viola tries to act like a boy.  There are romantic triangles and fun soccer scenes.  This is a great silly teen movie.  Enjoy it with a some popcorn and soda and be ready to laugh at the silliness.

reviewText: Take one ounce of Shakespeare, four hot bodied young actors, a few cases of mistaken identity, and soccer, and you have just a field full of fun.While very loosely based on Twelfth Night (and you really have to look hard for the hidden dialogue from the play) the story of a girl (Bynes) who must pose as her brother (Kirk) to play soccer and prove to the world that girls are equal to boys (if not better).  While everyone at the school must temporarily suspend reality to believe that Bynes even resembles, acts or sounds like her foot taller brother is something that makes the movie cheesy and fun (but at the same time addictive).Overall, the acting is good, the story is fun and it moves quickly.  If you are looking for high drama or bust your gut comedy, this is not it.  If you are looking for a fun movie that  makes you smile in a guilty pleasure sort of way... get this one.

reviewText: While the film itself only merits 3.5 stars - it's a run-of-the-mill teen comedy will the requisite eye-candy cast - the commentary track on the DVD earns this film a 5 star rating.I don't regularly listen to commentaries, but for some reason on this one I did, and am very glad to have done so... it is far funnier and more enjoyable than the film itself.The commentary features the young stars, the director and the writer.  What separates this commentary track from ordinary ones is how fun and personable the commentators are.  They sound like they are having a blast watching the movie together, and that spirit is infectious.Much of the commentary has the cast and director lightly poking fun at each other (especially targeting "Dakota Channing" Tatum, the film's alpha male, who can stand to take a little ribbing).  This might seem like it would get tedious, but I couldn't help but laugh along with these people for the duration of the track.If you own or plan on buying this DVD listening to the Cast audio commentary is a must!  enjoy.
summary: 5 stars for its hilarious, joyful commentary

reviewText: Viola (Bynes) is really upset when the girls' soccer team is at her high school is cut. The boys' team does not want girls on it (girls can't play with boys), so Viola decides to impersonate her brother Sebastian (Kirk) who is playing hookie in London trying to become a musician and is also starting at a new boarding school where no one knows him. As Sebastian, Viola can play soccer, and try to get revenge on her own school's team.The problem occurs when Viola falls in love with her roommate (Tatum). Of course, he is interested in Olivia (Ramsey), and Olivia has got her eye on Viola. The only thing that could make things more complicated for Viola is if her brother were to come home early; which he does.The film tries to portray Amanda Bynes as a teenage boy. She doesn't look the part, doesn't sound the part and has absolutely no clue how to act as a boy. It was painful and no where close to convincing. I don't know what the filmmakers were hoping to achieve; perhaps to show how stupid teenage guys can be and how ridiculous their behavior is. I'm not sure. However, none of this comes across because Bynes can't pull off being a guy. The film does have its share of moments. But overall, I'd skip this one if you can.

reviewText: I rented this after seeing the trailer on another DVD. It looked interesting because the woman playing a man was attractive. After "Boys Don't Cry," I needed reassurance.I was impressed with Amanda Bynes' ability to play a boy. My favorite line was "Which one would you rather see naked?""She's The Man" reminded me of a Lindsay Lohan movie, but it was a lot better. The soccer reminded me a lot of "Bend It Like Beckham" but a little less complicated and without the English accents."She's The Man" follows the Hollywood teen movie formula, but it has enough originality to keep you interested, and the last 30 minutes don't get all melancholy.By the way, the song toward the end in the "cheese" scene is "Hold You In My Arms" by Ray LaMontagne. It's not on the soundtrack CD.
